E-commerce Sequential Testing A/B Test Code¶

Goal: This notebook can help A/B Test practitioners plan for and execute experiments using Google Analytics 4 data. It transforms GA4 e-commerce event data into an experiment ready table where activity can be aggregated cumulatively for any date range.

Data in this form allows analysts to run useful pre-experiment analyses, including reviewing:

  1. historical daily metric activity data,

  2. cumulative mean and variance over time,

  3. expected error decay over time,

  4. samples size requirements by metric,

  5. metric distibutions for normality and skew,

  6. expected pvalues over time,

  7. and many other useful pre-experiment metrics.

Section X allows analysts to select a specific metric and repeatedly re-group visitors to test different experiment evaluation techniques. This section highlights some issues with underpowered tests on high variance, low frequency metrics like purchase count. Finally, Section XI reviews sequential testing methods that mitigate some problems associated with underpowered tests and false positives.

Sequential testing aside, this notebook illustrates the importance of choosing a single experiment metric, re-testing p-values above .01, and using 99% confidence intervals for websites performing many experiments as suggested by practitioners like Ron Kohavi. Moreover, analysts should make sure stakeholders understand uncertainty reflected in confidence intervals and what they mean about impact estimates. Knowing this will helps stakeholders decide how certain they need to be given costs of implementing changes.

Since no actual experiment was run, the code selects an arbitrary evaluation page and aggregates user activity post evaluation page visit to the end of a selected experiment period. Inputs are variables. They can easily be changed to run code on any page or set of events for any period.

Metrics evaluated are: purchase, purchase quantity, purchase bookings, engagement minutes, daily unique page visits, scroll, view_item, view_promotion, add_to_cart, begin_checkout, select_item, and select_promotion.

For future iterations of this code, it might be desireable to add null value counts or drop counts for each event parameter.

A. BIG QUERY ENGAGEMENT EVENTS MEANINGS¶

  1. page_view: Each time the page loads or the browser history state is changed by the active site. In this analysis, unique_pages calculates the number of unique urls visited per day.

Properties

  • page_title,

  • page_location (page URL),

  • page_referrer (previous page URL),

  • engagement_time_msec

  • session_engaged: An engaged session is a session that lasts longer than 10 seconds, has a conversion event, or has at least 2 pageviews or screenviews. Note: Bounce rate is the % of sesssions that were not engaged.

  1. scroll: This triggers when a visitor scrolls down the page of interest.

  2. user_engagement: When the app is in the foreground or webpage is in focus for at least one second. In this analysis, engage_mins aggregates this time in minutes.

  • engagement_time_msec
  1. click: Each time a user clicks a link that leads away from the current domain.

Properties

  • link_classes

  • link_domain

  • link_id

  • link_url

A. Historical Daily New Evaluation Page Visitors Plot¶

Goal: Plot daily new evaluation page (aka proposed experiment page) visitors. This helps analysts get a sense of daily expected traffic to the experiment page and estimate duration based on sample size requirements.

Conclusions:

a) The plot shows that daily page traffic jumped substantially between November and December.

b) In this case, the only pre-evaluation data available was from November 2020. As a rule of thumb, we should not run experiments or estimate experiment traffic from holidays or sale months like black friday unless central to what is being tested.

Notes: There are many ways to estimate page traffic for experiment duration based on sample size calculations. If you have fairly stable traffic, a fairly naive method involves simply taking the last month while avoiding months with holidays or unusual activity. Alternatively, we can get a pretty good idea of expected conversion rates by taking the rate of growth YoY of the prior month times the last years estimate for the experiment's month. Either way, its helpful to review at least 14 months to two years of time series data to see if estimates are historically reasonable.

IV. Cumulative Statistics over Time¶

Goal: For many experiments, user level experiment metrics accrued after exposure are calculated over the entire experiment period. For good websites attracting lots of repeat active users, metric variance will likely increase over time because visitors exposed early have more time to accrue metrics.

To mimic this, the section:

  1. Visualizes how metric means and variance accrue over time.

  2. Visualizes how 95% Wald confidence intervals as a percent of mean estimates for each metric decay over time. This helps stakeholders consider expected error ranges over time.

Note: 1) Since visitors are randomly bucketed into treatment/control groups in real time, groups should have similar numbers of early and late participants. 2) Analysts can discuss with stakeholders the pros and cons of reducing variance by evaluating metrics accrued within a specified window of hitting the experiment page. However, this strategy may miss indicators of longer term impacts from changes.

A. Calculate Cumulative Summary Statistics over Time Using For Loop¶

  1. The first for loop creates a dataframe with all unique experiment participant user ids appearing on(or before) the reference date (i) and assigns a 0 to each user_id in a column called post_count.

  2. The second for loop creates a dataframe with user_id and triggered_events counts as post_count for each adj_event_name(j) in event_array on(or before) the reference date (i).

  3. User Level Aggregation: The dataframe from the first loop is concatinated with the dataframe from the second and post_count is summed to the user level. Note: Summing drops 0 values for users that triggered the selected event but keeps those who did not.

  4. Calculate Statistics

B. Cumulative Mean over Time Plot¶

Conclusion:

a) add_to_cart and select_item are clearly behaving strangely as expected.

b) Most metrics appear fairly stable over time except purchase metrics. A mean that moves around a lot is likely a high variance event and will take longer to estimate.

c) Metrics with very small per user averages and high variance like purchase (orders) require very large sample sizes to estimate and may be impractical depending on site traffic.

C. Cumulative Standard Deviation over Time Plot¶

Conclusions: Some metrics like purchases (ie orders), purchase quantity(item counts), and bookings had jumps in standard deviations over time. This could be from a number of things.

  1. Offering users holiday coupons can cause skewed purchase behavior.

  2. The influx of visitors we saw at the end of the month could cause increased volatility. Particularly if it relates to lower/higher than normal quality leads that won't be repeated under normal circumstances.

Big jumps like that are an indicator that the period we are looking at may not be good for estimating normal conditions. Increased variance over time from repeat users should steadily trend upwards not wildly jump.

D. Confidence Interval Decay over Time Plot¶

Conclusions:

a) The purchase metrics have the highest error ranges at the end of the period.

b) Since the confidence interval decays faster, if user purchases are the metric of interest, it might be worth considering the use of begin checkout as a primary metric rather than purchase bookings or quantity.

c) add_to_cart and select_item do not appear to be functioning properly.

Notes:

  1. CI_Percent is the percent error for mean estimates based on confidence intervals. For example, the view_promotion confidence interval was +/- 8% after 30 days.

  2. Estimated 95% Two Sided Confidence Intervals were calculated using Welch's Standard Error.

SE = $\sqrt{\frac{S_T^2}{n_T}+\frac{S_C^2}{n_C}} * 1.97$

Daily counts were split in half to represent each group. ie n_c represents half the accrued visitors.

V. Sample Size Calculations¶

Goal: This section calculates sample size requirements to run an experiment for each metrics and estimates required experiment length to test for a detectable 5%+ effect (MDE). This value is needed for group sequential testing.

Required n Per Group (n) = $\frac{(\frac{\alpha}{2}_{crit} + 1-\beta_{crit})^2*2\sigma^2}{\delta^2} $

where $\delta$ is the absolute Minimum Detectable Effect size.

The values for $\sigma^2$ and a 5% $\delta$ were calculated from cumulative estimates at the end of the 30 day period from Table C in Section IV(A). Under normal circumstances, this would provide a more conservative estimate incorporating the impact of longer time frames to accrue metrics for some users.

Note: 1) Since significant volatilty was present during November, in a real experiment, we would likely pick a different time frame to estimate mean, standard deviation, and sample size. Increased variance leads to higher sample size requirements and uncharacteristically high daily traffic can lead to underestimating duration. However, in this case, this is the only data available from Big Query. 2) I used the absolute difference for MDE in the sample size formula but some fields instruct practitioners to use the standardized difference.

VI. Create Experiment Groups¶

Goal: During an A/B test, experiment participants are generally split into treatment and control groups as they arrive. In theory, this reduces group imbalance because one group is less likely to get more users that arrived day 1 than another. To mimic this, I use stratified sampling on first exposure date to create treatment and control groups.

Note: Function annotates with correlation for each group.

Step 3: Since pair plot compares all pairs of metrics, its best to select a few metrics of interest at a time and treatment status.

ie Metrics: engage_mins, purchase_bookings, begin_checkout, scroll, unique_pages, purchase_quantity, add_to_cart.

Conclusion:

a) As is usually the case, the distribution of most metrics is skewed left over 0 with a long tail. This happens often with website metrics because many users fail to engage in the activity and have 0 values. For example, many webpage visitors do not purchase anything. The general consensus is that with many observations skewed is not a problem. There are formulas that can be used to determine how many are required. There are also tests tailored specifically for skewed distributions that could be explored.

b) begin_checkout does not appear linearly related to purchase quantity or purchase amount. Unsurprisingly, starting the checkout process is independent of the quantity of what is in the cart. Since no linear relationship was present, if used as a metric, begin_checkout can probably be a binary variable without losing significant information.

c) We can observe in the data some expected linear relationships. For example, purchase quantity and revenue or unique pages and engagement minutes.

Note:

  1. If purchase count is extremely important, it would have to be monitored. Although caution must be taken to avoid multiple comparisons, in cases like these, product teams will sometimes include events like purchase count as guardrail metrics to make sure that the purchase flow is functioning.

  2. There are many additional factors to consider when choosing an experiment metric. Although purchases seem practical, a product relying on repeat users might prefer longer term oriented metrics like retention. Its important to strategize with product teams when picking a metric.

VIII. Maximum Sample Size Calculations¶

Note: When performing Group Sequential Tests, required sample sizes are adjusted to perserve power and provide a stopping point where the null is accepted. For an 95% O'Brien Flemming Test, a 20 stop test adjusts sample size by a factor of 1.05. See alpha adjustment ratios in VIII(A)ii. The test continues until a statistically significant result is reached or the max sample size is reached.

XI. Appendix - Sequential Testing Methods¶

A. Group Sequential Testing¶

Source: Group Sequential Methods with Applications to Clinical Trials (Turnbull et al.)

Notes: 1) Some sources claim group sequential testing can hurt power. Ability to detect no change.

Group sequential designs have been developed to efficiently test hypotheses using the Neyman-Pearson approach for statistical inference, where the goal is to decide how to act, while controlling error rates in the long run. Group sequential designs do not have the goal to quantify the strength of evidence, or provide accurate estimates of the effect size (Proschan et al., 2006). Group Sequential Designs (Lakens) at 9.

  1. Some sources discuss using stagewise means and standard deviations in each calculation rather than the cumulative. ie Only the new experiment participants during the period. Probably to keep variance stable across groups. See rpact https://www.rpact.org/vignettes/getting-started/rpact_step-by-step_tutorial/

Next Steps:

Think about whether controlling for cumulative variance becoming larger over time due to earlier participants having more time to accrue outcomes is necessary? Uber uses a method called delete-a-group jackknife variance estimation to adjust for user correlation across multiple days.

i. Pocock's Test¶

a) Adjusted Critical Values¶

$Z_k = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2mK \sigma^2 }} ( \sum_{i=1}^{mk}X_A - \sum_{i=1}^{mk}X_B)$

Where m is group size and k is the number of groups. k is chosen before experiment start.

Adjusted Critical Values are based on the # of checkins and chosen sinificance level (a)

b) Adjusted Alphas¶

Adjusted Alpha Threshold:

$\alpha' = 2 * (1- \Phi (AdjustedCriticalValue))$

Example: P-Value Threshold¶

K = 5 and $\alpha$=.05

Adjusted Critical Value = 2.413 based on chart above.

0.015821819570605467

c) Maximum Sample Size (Inflation Factors)¶

Required sample size(n) for test needs to be scaled up by a ratio Rp($ K, \beta, \alpha$) * $n_{group}$

- Sample Size Notation / Formulas for Example Calculation:¶

Required n Per Group (n) = $\frac{(\frac{\alpha}{2}_{crit} + 1-\beta_{crit})^2*2\sigma^2}{\delta^2} $

Note: Percent point function (inverse of cdf — percentiles).

$\alpha_{crit95} = \phi^{-1}(.975)$ = norm.ppf(.975, loc=0, scale=1) = 1.96

$1-\beta_{crit90} = \phi^{-1}(.9)$ = norm.ppf(.9, loc=0, scale=1) = 1.28

$\sigma^2$ = 4 , MDE($\delta$) = 1 , K = 5

The test stops at 102 participants per group and evaluation can occur every m = 21 participants.

d) Stopping Rule (Reject Null if)¶

$\mid \sum_{i=1}^{mk}X_A - \sum_{i=1}^{mk}X_B \mid$ $\geq adj_{crit}(2.413)* \sqrt{2*n_{group}\sigma^2}$

Note: The enhanced critical value remains constant over each stop.

If not rejected by the K stop, the null wins.

ii. O'Brien & Fleming's Test¶

a) Adjusted Critical Values¶

This test does not have constant critical values. Constant critical values are adjusted by a formula that depends on which K you are on.

$ crit_k = C_{const}*\sqrt{ \frac{K_{total}}{k_{stop} }} $

Example:

k = 2. ie Second Evaluation Stops

K = 5. ie 5 Total Evaluations

alpha = .05

3.2255232133717473

b) Adjusted Alpha¶

Adjusted Alpha Threshold:

$\alpha' = 2 * (1- \Phi (AdjustedCriticalValue*\sqrt{ \frac{K_{total}}{k_{stop} }}) )$

Adjusted Critical Values are based on total check ins(K), the check in number(k) ie first check in k=1, and chosen sinificance level (a)

Example (cont...):

k = 2. ie Second Evaluation Stops

K = 5. ie 5 Total Evaluations

0.001257426382596627

c) Maximum Sample Size (Inflation Factors)¶

Required sample size(n) for test needs to be scaled up by a ratio Rp($ K, \beta, \alpha$) * $n_{group}$

The test stops at 87 participants per group and evaluation can occur every m = 18 participants.

d) Stopping Rule (Reject Null if)¶

$\mid \sum_{i=1}^{mk}X_A - \sum_{i=1}^{mk}X_B \mid$ $\geq crit_{AdjConst}(2.040)*\sqrt{5/k_{stop}}*\sqrt{2*n_{group}\sigma^2}$

Notes: 1)The enhanced critical value changes by a factor of $\sqrt{K_{Total}/k_{stop}}$ for each stop.

2)If not rejected by the K stop, the null wins. 3) $ 2*n_{group} $ assumes equal group sizes. 4)Equation shifts $ \sqrt{2*n_{group}\sigma^2} $ to the right instead of keeping it in the left side denominator.

Georgiev at 169.

where t is the fraction completed. ie .8 for 80%

iv. O'Brien Fleming like (DeMets)¶

a) Adjusted Alpha Threshold:

$\alpha' = 2 * (1- \Phi (\frac{\phi^{-1}(1-\alpha/2)}{\sqrt{t}}) )$ One Sided (Georgiev Version)

$\alpha' = 4 * (1- \Phi (\frac{\phi^{-1}(1-\alpha/4)}{\sqrt{t}}) )$ Two Sided

where t is the fraction completed. ie .8 for 80%

Notes: Requires equally spaced looks. No requirement that number or timing of looks specified in advance. However, decision to implement should not be based on results.

b) O'Brien Fleming like Spending Function Plots (Georgiev)¶

v. Kim & DeMets Power Family¶

a) Adjusted Alpha Threshold:

$\alpha' = \alpha * t^\rho$

where $\rho$ is generally between 0 and 3 selected by the tester and t is the fraction completed. ie .8 for 80%.

rho notes: The value of rho ranges from 0 to 3. 3 resembles O'Brien Fleming test. 1 is uniform. 1.5 falls in the middle. Under 1 allows stopping very early. A high rho penalizes early test results more. Stopping too early leads to greater bias in point estimates. This is known as conditional bias. See Maximum Conditional Likelihood Estimates by DeMets. https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/09622802221122445 See also DeMets Restricted Conditional Confidence Interval and Exact Conditional Confidence Intervals.

C. Sequential Testing - Always Valid P-Values¶

i. mSPRT (Optimizely Version)¶

Always Valid p-values

Source: Peeking at A/B Tests (Johari et al)

Formulas / Notation (Mixture Likelihood Ratios)¶

$\Lambda_n^{H,\theta_0}$ = $\sqrt{ \frac{2\sigma^2}{2\sigma^2 + n\tau^2}}* exp(\frac{n^2\tau^2(\bar Y_n- \bar X_n-\theta_0)^2}{4\sigma^2(2\sigma^2 + n\tau^2)})$

where

$\theta_0$ is the difference of the null hypothesis and $\tau^2$ is the variance of the mixing distribution.

Mixing Distribution(H): $H$ ~ $N(\theta_0, \tau^2)$

Note: The mixing distribution H should match the distribution of true effects across prior experiments. 1 discussed for rate in paper. In a recent paper, Kohavi et al. gives experiment success rates between 8 to 33%.

Source: A/B Testing Intuition Busters (Kohavi et al.)
